Things that stood out during analysis:

  • Some participants never adjust their first affect rating in the second affect rating or very rarely. This might be an artifact of the experiment program. After submitting affect rating 1, this value is saved and used as start point for affect rating 2. Therefore, participants could make it an easy strategy not to change affect rating 1. Five participants never change affect rating 1. Our main interest in this task are the affect ratings. Will we keep these participants in the data for analysis?

Lets do some sanity checks with plots

  1. Are participants happier when they get more money?
    Test: Outcome ~ affect rating 1
    Outcome: From visual inspection you can see that with increasing offer participants report to have more positive affect. This seems to be a nice linear effect
data$f_outcomeChoice <- factor(data$outcomeChoice)
ggplot(data, aes(f_outcomeChoice, affect1, fill = f_outcomeChoice)) + 
  geom_violin() + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = fivecolors) +
  theme_bw() + labs(x = 'Outcome', y = 'Affect rating 1', fill = '')

  1. Are participants still happier when they get more money after knowing what they could have had?
    Test: Outcome ~ affect rating 2
    Outcome: Again, from visual inspection you can see that with increasing offer participants report to have more positive affect. This seems to be a nice linear effect. Maybe a bit more variace than affect rating 1.
ggplot(data, aes(f_outcomeChoice, affect2, fill = f_outcomeChoice)) + 
  geom_violin() + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = fivecolors) +
  theme_bw() + labs(x = 'Outcome', y = 'Affect rating 1', fill = '')

Counterfactual thinking is based on the idea that people feel regret when they see the outcome that they could have had, precisely an aversive emotional state that is elicited by adiscrepancy in the outcome values of chosen vs.unchosen actions. (from buckholtz, 2016, PNAS). This leads to my second hypothesis/check:

  1. Participants should update their affect rating 1 from rating 2. Do participants do this?

Test: affect1 - affect2 > 0 Outcome: Well It seems that participants dont really change their affect ratings that much.. Lets explore further, make a note of this and discuss with Josh.

data$changeAffect <- data$affect1 - data$affect2
ggplot(data, aes(f_outcomeChoice, changeAffect, fill = f_outcomeChoice)) + 
  geom_violin() + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = fivecolors) +
  theme_bw() + labs(x = 'Outcome', y = 'Affect rating 1')

Next, I want to see if keeping affect rating 2 the same compared to affect rating 1 is a common strategy.

It seems that this is quite a common strategy. That seems problematic to me.
5 participants never changed affect rating 1.
18 particpants changed their affect rating in less than 10% of the trials.

#Are there participants that never change the rating?
notchanged <- data.frame(table(subset(data, changeAffect == 0)$subject))
names(notchanged) <- c('subject','freq')

#5 participants never changed their second affect rating. What was their affect?
nrow(notchanged[notchanged$freq == 55,])
## [1] 5
#18 participants changed their affect rating in less than 10% of trials
nrow(notchanged[notchanged$freq > 55*0.9,])
## [1] 18
#Save subject numbers
noAffectChangeSubs <- notchanged[notchanged$freq == 55,]$subject
noAffectChangeSubs90 <- notchanged[notchanged$freq > 55*0.9 & notchanged$freq != 55,]$subject

#Distribution
ggplot(notchanged, aes(freq)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, color = 'black', fill = fivecolors[1]) + 
  theme_bw() + labs(x = 'Number of trials in which participants did not update affect rating 2.\nRed line indicates 90% of trials.') + 
  geom_vline(xintercept = 49.5, size = 2, color = fivecolors[4])

How bad does that look for the individual participants. Did they learn that this is the easy way out?
